    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. that's a good start. could you add a little more warmth to the closing? like, we really want them to feel like we'd actually reach out if another role opens up, rather than it just being a standard canned response. also, maybe make the part about the cloud stack experience sound a bit less like a disqualification and more like a \"perfect timing\" thing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, absolutely! Adding warmth and that specific \"perfect timing\" nuance is a great idea, and it's exactly the kind of detail that makes a rejection feel less like a cold transaction and more like a strategic, albeit difficult, alignment of forces.\n\nHere is the revised draft with those tweaks, plus a few more thoughts on how to keep the conversation going without burning the bridge.\n\n***\n\n**Subject:** Update on Your Application for Senior Developer Role\n\nHi [Candidate Name],\n\nThank you so much for taking the time to interview for the Senior Developer position here in Austin. We were genuinely impressed by your system design skills and your strong alignment with our culture. It was a pleasure getting to know you.\n\nWhile your background is impressive, we have decided to move forward with a candidate who has slightly more direct experience with our specific cloud stack. We view this less as a disqualification and more as a matter of perfect timing; their current availability aligns just right with our immediate infrastructure needs, whereas your expertise would be a fantastic asset for a future project where that specific stack might evolve or shift.\n\nWe truly value the time you spent with us and would love to keep you in mind for future opportunities where your specific skillset might",
